{
  "project": "fixture-shop",
  "title": "HMAC Signature Verification in verify.php",
  "slug": "hmac-signature-verification-verify-php",
  "date": "2026-07-17",
  "depth": "intro",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "name": "HMAC Signature Verification",
      "definition": "A technique where both sender and receiver independently compute a keyed cryptographic hash (HMAC) over a shared payload using a secret key, then compare the results to prove the message was sent by a party who knows the secret and has not been tampered with in transit."
    },
    {
      "name": "Constant-Time Comparison",
      "definition": "A comparison algorithm that always takes the same amount of time to execute regardless of how many bytes match between the two inputs, preventing timing attacks where an attacker could learn the correct value by measuring response duration."
    }
  ],
  "files": ["src/verify.php"],
  "commit": "aba7e1e",
  "sources": [],
  "lesson": "The `verify()` function in `src/verify.php` decides whether an incoming webhook really came from the payment gateway. It recomputes an [[fixture-shop/_glossary#HMAC Signature Verification|HMAC-SHA256 signature]] over the raw request payload using the shared secret, then compares that against the signature header the sender provided. The comparison uses PHP's `hash_equals()`, a [[fixture-shop/_glossary#Constant-Time Comparison|constant-time comparison]], so an attacker cannot learn the correct signature byte by byte from response timing."
}

